cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SY, cs.MM, cs.AR. 

The paper deals with the performance of radio resource slicing for the three generic services of 5G, which involves communication theory, information theory, and networking. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) are the most likely categories. The paper also proposes a design principle and considers different decoding architectures, which fall under the category of cs.SY (Systems and Control). Additionally, the paper deals with massive machine-type communications (mMTC) and ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC), which are related to cs.MM (Multimedia) and cs.AR (Hardware Architecture).
